..TEXT:
|secondo la sentenza di Platone~: "In the ^Timaeus~,
which was accessible to Dante in the Latin paraphrase of
Chalcidius.  Dante's direct knowledge of Plato was doubtless
confined to this one dialogue.  The doctrine ascribed to Plato,
implicitly here and explicitly in ^Conv.~ [IV, xxi, 2], goes
somewhat beyond the warrant of the text either in the Greek or
Latin" (TC).  "Plato, in his ^Timaeus~ (41, 42), says that the
creator of the universe assigned each soul to a star, whence they
were to be sown in the vessels of time.  `He who lived well
during his appointed time was to return to the star which was his
habitation, and there he would have a blessed and suitable
existence.'  Jowett's translation. -- Dante's doubt has arisen
from the words of Piccarda (Canto III, 50, 51), which implied
that her station was in the sphere of the Moon" (Norton).  This
doctrine is contrary to Christian faith.  See Thomas Aquinas,
^Summa theol.~ III, Suppl., q. 97, a. 5.  "Plato's theory
appealed strongly to some of the early Christian theologians, but
had to be abandoned after 540, when the Council of Constantinople
decided that every soul is created by God at the birth of its
body" (Gr).
