..TEXT:
|de la celestial c'ha men salita~: Of their rank in
the celestial sphere, the Empyrean, where they occupy the lowest
seats, farthest from God.  And what these spirits say of
themselves applies in turn to each of the spheres that lie ahead
and above.  The poet's invention of this whole scheme is
noteworthy, and the reader has only to consider how
unsatisfactory (if not impossible) it would have been had the
pilgrim risen immediately and directly to the Empyrean, in the
first canto of the ^Paradiso~, and remained there for thirty-two
cantos!  By such a device, instead, his journey can pass
eventfully upwards by degrees or stages, each stage higher than
the last, like so many rungs of a ladder, reaching upward all the
way to God.
..TCHR:
