..TEXT:
|l'onor de la influenza e 'l biasmo~: The influence
of the stars was granted in the argument of Marco Lombardo
(^Purg.~ XVI, 73) and was generally taken for granted in
medieval thought.  The most striking instance, in Dante's poem,
will come when Dante the pilgrim reaches the constellation of
Gemini under which he was born, where (^Par.~ XXII, 112-123) he
acknowledges that he owes all his genius to those "glorious"
stars.  Indeed, the notion is fundamental to the whole structure
of the ^Paradiso~, for the souls seen in each of the planets were
variously influenced by these heavenly bodies.
..TCHR:
